 sometimes found in the Gaelicized form <b>Pléamonn</b>.","German: variant of   Flemming  , cognate with 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Flemings","meanings":["English: plural form of   Fleming  .","Americanized form of Flemish <b>Vleminckx</b>: patronymic from <b>Vleminck</b>, an ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle Dutch <i>vleminc</i>."]},{"name":"Flanders","meanings":["English: ethnic name from Middle English <i>Fla(u)ndres</i> ‘Flanders’, denoting someone from Flanders, a historical region covering parts of modern-day Belgium, France, and the Netherlands. Compare   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Fleeman","meanings":["English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flemming","meanings":["German: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle High German <i>vlaeminc</i>. People from Flanders spread throughout Germany, as well as England, in the Middle Ages as clothmakers and dyers.","English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flamenco","meanings":["Spanish: ethnic name from <i>flamenco</i> ‘Fleming, Flemish person’ (see   Fleming  )."]}]},{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Anna Fleming was born in 1328, in Fermoy, County Cork, Ireland, her father, William Fleming, was 23 and her mother, Mrs. William Fleming, was 18. She married David de la Roche Lord Roche in 1348, in Fermoy, County Cork, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1350, in her hometown, at the age of 22."},"et":{"1328–1350":"1328–1350","1300–1374":"1300–1374","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1305":"1305","1348":"1348","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1387":"1387","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1328":"1328","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1328–1350":"1328–1350","1300–1374":"1300–1374","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1305":"1305","1348":"1348","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1387":"1387","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1328":"1328","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Irlanti"},"fr":{"1328–1350":"1328–1350","1300–1374":"1300–1374","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1305–Male":"1305–Décédé","1310–Female":"1310–Décédée","1305":"1305","1348":"1348","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1387":"1387","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1328":"1328","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Irlande","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Anna Fleming est née en 1328, à Fermoy, County Cork, Irlande, son père, William Fleming, avait 23 ans et sa mère, Mrs. William Fleming, avait 18 ans. Elle a épousé David de la Roche Lord Roche en 1348, à Fermoy, County Cork, Irlande. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée en 1350, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 22 ans."},"de":{"1328–1350":"1328–1350","1300–1374":"1300–1374","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1305–Male":"1305–Verstorben","1310–Female":"1310–Verstorben","1305":"1305","1348":"1348","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1387":"1387","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1328":"1328","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"